To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with an Arduino, you can follow these steps:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to your Arduino board. The sensor is powered by the Arduino via VCC and GND pins. Connect the analog output pin of the LM35 to the analog input pin A0 of the Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

2. Connect the LCD to the Arduino. You will need to use the LiquidCrystal_I2C library for this. Install the library in Arduino IDE by going to Tools > Manage Libraries, searching for "LiquidCrystal I2C", and installing the library by Frank de Brabander [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

3. Connect a 10K Ohm potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The first pin of the potentiometer should be connected to +VCC, the second pin to pin 3 of the LCD, and the third pin to GND [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

4. Upload the code to the Arduino to read the temperature from the LM35 sensor and display it on the LCD. You can find example code and detailed explanations in the tutorials mentioned in the references [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)] [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

The error message is telling you that the `using enum` feature requires C++20 or later. By default, Visual Studio uses an older version of the C++ standard.

To enable C++20 in Visual Studio 2022, you can follow these steps:

1. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer.
2. Select "Properties" from the context menu.
3. In the Properties window, go to "Configuration Properties" > "General".
4. Look for the "C++ Language Standard" option and set it to "ISO C++20 Standard (/std:c++20)".
5. Click "Apply" and then "OK" to save the changes.

The design process is a series of steps that product teams follow during the formulation of a product from start to finish. The design process is an essential part of product design, and it typically includes the following stages: 1. Empathize with users 2. Define the problem 3. Ideate solutions 4. Prototype ideas 5. Test solutions Let's break down each stage in more detail: 1. Empathize with users: The first step is to understand the users' needs, wants, and pain points. This involves conducting user research through interviews, surveys, and observations to gain insights into their experiences and challenges. 2. Define the problem: Based on the insights gathered from user research, the team defines the core problem they are trying to solve. This step involves creating user personas, user journey maps, and problem statements to guide the design process. 3. Ideate solutions: In this stage, the team brainstorms and generates a wide range of potential solutions to the defined problem. This can involve sketching, mind mapping, and other creative techniques to explore different ideas and approaches. 4. Prototype ideas: The team creates low-fidelity prototypes of the most promising ideas to visualize and test them. These prototypes can be simple sketches, wireframes, or interactive mockups that allow the team to refine and iterate on their concepts.
